503Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.2hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.2.xml1.2.4.2hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4          \overline {F}^q(A)         =  \sum _{q' \geqslant  q} A^{p',q'}.       \tag{1.2.4.2}       

We have

504Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.3hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.4.3.xml1.2.4.3hodge-theory-ii-1.2.4          \operatorname {Gr} _F^p \operatorname {Gr} _{ \overline {F}}^q(A)         = A^{p,q}.       \tag{1.2.4.3}

html:ol.html:li:
If F and \overline {F} are n-opposite, and if we set
          \begin {cases}           A^{p,q} = 0           & \text {for }p+q \neq  n          \\ A^{p,q} = F^p(A) \cap \overline {F}^q(A)           & \text {for }p+q=n          \end {cases}       
then A is the direct sum of the A^{p,q}, and F and \overline {F} come from the bigrading A^{p,q} of A by the procedure of .

