525Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.2hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.2.xml1.2.11.2hodge-theory-ii-lemma-1.2.11         F^p(A)         =  \sum _{p' \geqslant  p} A_0^{p',q'}       \tag{1.2.11.2}       

526Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.3hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.3.xml1.2.11.3hodge-theory-ii-lemma-1.2.11          \overline {F}^q(A)         =  \sum _{q' \geqslant  q} A_1^{p',q'}.       \tag{1.2.11.3}

By symmetry, it suffices to prove the claims concerning i=0. Set A_0= \bigoplus A_0^{p,q} and define filtrations W and F on A_0 by the equations of . The canonical map i from A_0 to A is compatible with the filtrations W and F. Furthermore, by , \operatorname {Gr} _W(i) is an isomorphism, and induces isomorphisms of graded objects
527Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.4hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.2.11.4.xml1.2.11.4hodge-theory-ii-lemma-1.2.11 \sum _{p+q=n} A_0^{p,q} \xrightarrow { \sim } \operatorname {Gr} _W^{-n}(A) = \sum _{p+q=n} A^{p,q}. \tag{1.2.11.4}
The morphism i is thus an isomorphism, and the A_0^{p,q} give a bigrading of A.

Let (A,F) be a filtered object with finite filtration, and TF the filtration of TA by its sub-objects TF^p(A) (these are sub-objects since T is left exact). If \operatorname {Gr} _F(A) is T-acyclic, then the F^p(A) are T-acyclic as successive extensions of T-acyclic objects. The image under T of the sequence 0 \to F^{p+1}(A) \to F^p(A) \to \operatorname {Gr} ^p(A) \to 0
is thus exact, and
556Equationhodge-theory-ii-equation-1.4.2.1hodge-theory-ii-equation-1.4.2.1.xml1.4.2.1hodge-theory-ii-1.4.2 \operatorname {Gr} _{FT}TA \xrightarrow { \sim } T \operatorname {Gr} _FA. \tag{1.4.2.1}

Let K be a complex.
We denote by \tau _{ \leqslant  p}(K) the following subcomplex:
        \tau _{ \leqslant  p}(K)^n       =  \begin {cases}         K^n         & \text {for }n<p        \\ \operatorname {Ker} (d)         & \text {for }n=p        \\ 0         & \text {for }n>p.        \end {cases}

The subcomplexes \sigma _{ \geqslant  p}(K) of K
        \sigma _{ \geqslant  p}(K)^n       =  \begin {cases}         0         & \text {if }n<p        \\ K^n         & \text {if }n \geqslant  p        \end {cases}     
define a biregular filtration, called the stupid filtration of K.

